  "prompt": "What are some Japanese names that mean water?",
  "response": "In Japanese, several names are associated with the meaning of water, either directly or through related concepts. Here are a few examples:\n\n### For Girls:\n1. **Mizuho (\u745e\u7a42)** - This name can mean \"abundant rice\" but includes \"mizu\" (\u6c34), which means water.\n2. **Sui (\u6c34)** - A simple name that directly means \"water.\"\n3. **Mizuki (\u6c34\u6708)** - A name that can mean \"water moon\" or \"moon over water.\"\n4. **Aqua (\u30a2\u30af\u30a2)** - A modern name derived from the Latin word for water.\n\n### For Boys:\n1. **Haruki (\u6625\u8f1d)** - While this name primarily means \"spring radiance,\" it can also evoke images of flowing water in spring.\n2. **Kaito (\u6d77\u6597)** - This name can mean \"ocean\" (\u6d77) combined with various other kanji, related to water themes.\n3. **Mizuki (\u6c34\u5e0c)** - Similar to the girl's name, this name can mean \"hope of water.\"\n\n### Unisex:\n1. **Sui (\u6c34)** - Again, this simple name can be used for any gender and means \"water.\"\n2. **Mizuto (\u6c34\u6597)** - A name that can incorporate \"mizu\" (water) along with other meanings, often used as a first name for any gender.\n\nThese names can have various interpretations and nuances depending on the kanji used and personal context.",
